                <div class="meta">
                    <h3>jaygurudev das</h3>
                    <span class="date">
                        10 Mar 2022
                    </span>
                </div>
            </header>
             <div class="body">"When there is an epidemic disease, an antiseptic vaccine protects a person from the attack of such an epidemic. Similarly, food offered to Lord Viṣṇu and then taken by us makes us sufficiently resistant to material affection, and one who is accustomed to this practice is called a devotee of the Lord."
BG. 3.14 purport
Question: Was Srila Prabhupada another vaccination preacher???</div>
        </article>
        <article class="comment">
            <header class="clearfix">
                <div class="meta">
                    <h3>Manidhara das</h3>
                    <span class="date">
                        10 Mar 2022
                    </span>
                </div>
            </header>
             <div class="body">Answer to Jaygurudev das:
Certainly not! Srila Prabhupada used ocassionaly known terms to illustrate the sastric point he made. As already mentioned, how could Srila Prabhupada recommend vaccination as He was negligent even to alleopathic or even ayurvedic medicine?
His point was simple: there is no material solution to material problem, disease as such can be only eliminated by achievement of spiritual body.
He left the option that "we can try, but why to take such risk when the result is uncertain. That vaccination automaticaly protects from disease is already proven wrong. Some vaccinated people get sick anyway.
That vaccination can kill somebody is already proven. Such cases are already known to me a complete diletant in these matters.
Would Srila Prabhupada encourage us to take blindly shelter at any women or man dressed in white called "doctor" and inject our bodies with complete uknown chemical? Certainly not.
But he used examples of this sort to make his point more understandable.
Here an example:
When Srila Prabhupada said that "sexlife is a proof of mans health", did he encouraged sex life? Certainly not.
When he said that piggs get very strong by eating stool as it is very nutricious, did he encouraged us to eat stool?
Certainly not.
And so and so on.
So miquoting His Divine Grace as it is commonly done today by irresponsible individuals leads to further diviation and doubt. Is there anywhere one quote to be found where Srila Prabhupada urged his disciples that they MUST get vaccinated? Sofar nobody could find one. And still some of his so-called followers dare
to use him for their own agenda. Such fellows should be rejected.</div>
        </article>
